{"summary":"Accept fr-13-36f0aa72 and fr-13-a74a46a6 as real correctness/idempotency fixes. Reject fr-13-ca8af530 because it would undo intentional legacy backfill behavior, and reject fr-13-8f43b7ad because it identifies an ordering limitation but proposes only test/documentation rather than a corrective change.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-13-ca8af530","decision":"reject","rationale":"`collapse_task_run_attempts` already intentionally merges a legacy open row with a later named terminal row when bead/project/started_at uniquely identify the same attempt, and there is an explicit test covering that behavior. The fallback to `unique_open_legacy_group_index` is also guarded by uniqueness, so it is the mechanism that preserves legacy completion backfill rather than an accidental cross-run merge. Adding an `entry.run_id.is_none()` guard would split attempts that the write/update path already treats as one repaired attempt."},{"amendment_id":"fr-13-8f43b7ad","decision":"reject","rationale":"This points at a genuine weakness of using `started_at` as the sole recency signal, but the proposed amendment does not fix that weakness. A regression test would either codify the current wrong result or fail without an accompanying behavioral change, and documentation alone would rely on a monotonicity assumption that the code does not enforce. A real remedy needs a stronger causal ordering signal or explicit invariant enforcement, not just more coverage."},{"amendment_id":"fr-13-36f0aa72","decision":"accept","rationale":"`compare_task_run_recency` currently ranks a same-`started_at` terminal attempt above a later retry that is still running because it compares `finished_at` before any tie-break that distinguishes attempts. `reconcile_snapshot_from_lineage` then uses that result to compute `active_bead` and progress, so the snapshot can report no active work while a retry is actually running. That is a concrete correctness bug, and it needs a deterministic same-timestamp tie-break plus a regression test."},{"amendment_id":"fr-13-a74a46a6","decision":"accept","rationale":"The partial-write gap is real: `record_bead_start` persists lineage and snapshot before appending the start journal event, so a journal failure can leave behind a durable running row. Named callers recover because `run_id` lets `record_task_run_start` reuse that row, but runless callers only recover if they repeat the exact original `started_at`; a normal retry with a new timestamp falls into the `already active` path and strands the partial write. Widening recovery for the single unambiguous running attempt is a sound idempotency fix and should be regression-tested."}]}